Actually this does not work for the dashboard-plugin when rendering {{dashboard.vm}} as the context does not know about "authcontext". I would like to see this as default context element there, too.

*Use Case:*

We needed this as workaround for JRA-2364 -- _Hide Time Tracking estimates from certain users (e.g. customers)_ as we had to prevent that customers can add gadgets with time tracking information. Our solution was to set maxGadgets to "0" for them and only allow them to use preconfigured dashboards:

{code}
#if (!$authcontext.user.inGroup('${showtimetracking.groupname}'))
  #set($maxGadgets = 0)
#end
{code}

Where {{showtimetracking.groupname}} is set on compilation through resource filtering.

*Workaround:*

As described in [Confluence|http://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Customising+interface+based+on+user%27s+role?focusedCommentId=217743856#comment-217743856]:

* Add a dependency to the dashboard-plugin-POM:
{code:xml}
<dependency>
  <groupId>com.atlassian.jira</groupId>
  <artifactId>atlassian-jira</artifactId>
  <version>4.X.X</version>
  <scope>provided</scope>
</dependency>
{code}
* Change {{DashboardView.java}} to provide the authcontext:
{code:java}
context.put("authcontext", ComponentManager.getInstance().getJiraAuthenticationContext());
{code}

